<figure class="pc-lens">
  <figcaption>How to read Phillips-curve evidence without over-interpreting scatterplots</figcaption>
  <div class="pc-lens-grid">
    <article>
      <h3>Observed Correlation</h3>
      <p>Scatterplots of inflation versus unemployment/output gap can shift across periods.</p>
      <ul>
        <li>can flatten, steepen, or flip with changing shocks</li>
        <li>also depends on policy regime and expectation anchoring</li>
      </ul>
    </article>
    <article>
      <h3>Structural Slope kappa</h3>
      <p>The slope parameter in NKPC measures the causal inflation response to real pressure.</p>
      <ul>
        <li>not directly observed in raw scatterplots</li>
        <li>requires identification strategy and controls</li>
      </ul>
    </article>
    <article>
      <h3>Exam-Safe Interpretation</h3>
      <p>A weaker correlation does not automatically prove a flatter structural Phillips curve.</p>
      <ul>
        <li>expected inflation can shift the data cloud</li>
        <li>supply shocks can bias reduced-form estimates</li>
      </ul>
    </article>
  </div>
</figure>

